<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
LaunchAgent template for chord. `scripts/install-launchagent.sh`
substitutes @@APP@@ with the absolute path to Chord.app (the one
the user actually installed — /Applications, ~/Applications, or
a build location) and writes the result to
~/Library/LaunchAgents/com.chord.chord.plist.

Why a LaunchAgent and not a daemon: chord needs the user's
Accessibility grant + frontmost-app notifications, both of which
are session-scoped. A system-wide LaunchDaemon wouldn't get
either.

EnvironmentVariables/PATH mirrors focusfx's discovery: launchd's
default PATH lacks Homebrew / asdf / mise, so a `action-shell`
binding calling brew-installed tools (yabai, fzf, …) would
silently fail without this. The list is the standard Homebrew /
system PATH; if the user has things in unusual places, the
binding can prefix its own `command -v` resolution.
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <key>Label</key>
    <string>com.chord.chord</string>

    <key>ProgramArguments</key>
    <array>
        <string>@@APP@@/Contents/MacOS/chord</string>
    </array>

    <key>RunAtLoad</key>
    <true/>

    <key>KeepAlive</key>
    <true/>

    <key>ProcessType</key>
    <string>Interactive</string>

    <key>StandardOutPath</key>
    <string>/tmp/chord-launchd.log</string>
    <key>StandardErrorPath</key>
    <string>/tmp/chord-launchd.log</string>

    <key>EnvironmentVariables</key>
    <dict>
        <key>PATH</key>
        <string>/opt/homebrew/bin:/opt/homebrew/sbin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin:/usr/sbin:/sbin</string>
    </dict>
</dict>
</plist>
